content.problemStatement:
**Code blocks in C++** are defined using curly braces `{ }`, which help in structuring and organizing your code efficiently. They play a vital role in controlling the scope of variables and grouping related statements together. Proper indentation, though not required by the compiler, is highly recommended for better readability.

Code blocks allow multiple statements to be treated as a single unit of execution, especially within functions, loops, and conditionals.

**Syntax:**
```cpp
{
    // Statements inside the block
}
```

---

**Example:**
```cpp
#include  // Include the iostream library for input and output operations

using namespace std; // Use the standard namespace to avoid prefixing with std::

// Main function where the program execution starts
int main() {
    {
        // Start of a block
        cout << "This is a block!"; // Print a message to the console
        // End of the block
    }
    // Code outside the block (if any) would execute here
  return 0;
}
```
**Output:**
```default
This is a block!
```

